[[Image:Bartlett-Ranking BGD(2004).jpg|frame|right|PRA ranking exercise being carried out by members of a Farmer Field School in Bangladesh, 2004]]'''Participatory rural appraisal''' ('''PRA''') is an approach used by [[non-governmental organizations]] (NGOs) and other agencies involved in [[international development]]. The approach aims to incorporate the knowledge and opinions of rural people in the planning and management of development projects and programmes.<ref name="Chambers origins">{{cite journal |last=Chambers |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Chambers (development scholar) |date=July 1994 |title=The origins and practice of participatory rural appraisal |journal=[[World Development (journal)|World Development]] |volume=22 |issue=7 |pages=953–969 |doi=10.1016/0305-750X(94)90141-4 |url=http://www.parkdatabase.com/documents/download/1994_the_origins_and_practice_of_participatory_rural_appraisal.pdf}}</ref><ref name="Castelloe Gamble">{{cite book |last1=Castelloe |first1=Paul |last2=Gamble |first2=Dorothy N. |date=2005 |chapter=Participatory methods in community practice: popular education and participatory rural appraisal |editor1-last=Weil |editor1-first=Marie |editor2-last=Reisch |editor2-first=Michael |title=Handbook of community practice |location=Thousand Oaks, CA |publisher=[[Sage Publications]] |pages=261–275 |isbn=076192177X |oclc=55008364 |doi=10.4135/9781452220819.n13 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=G12A1N3uW5AC&pg=PA261}}</ref><ref name="Narayanasamy">{{cite book |last=Narayanasamy |first=N. |date=2009 |title=Participatory rural appraisal: principles, methods and application |location=Los Angeles |publisher=[[Sage Publications]] |isbn=9788178298856 |oclc=265732154 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=w_WHAwAAQBAJ}}</ref>

== Origins ==

The philosophical roots of participatory rural appraisal techniques can be traced to activist adult education methods such as those of [[Paulo Freire]] and the study clubs of the [[Antigonish Movement]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Flower |first1=Charlotte |last2=Mincher |first2=Paul |last3=Rimkus |first3=Susan |date=2000 |title=Overview—participatory processes in the North |journal=PLA Notes |volume=38 |pages=14–18 |url=http://pubs.iied.org/G01883/}}</ref> In this view, an actively involved and empowered local population is essential to successful rural community development. [[Robert Chambers (development scholar)|Robert Chambers]], a key exponent of PRA, argued that the approach owes much to "the Freirian theme, that poor and exploited people can and should be enabled to analyze their own reality."<ref>{{cite book |last=Chambers |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Chambers (development scholar) |date=1997 |title=Whose reality counts?: putting the first last |location=London |publisher=[[Intermediate Technology Development Group|Intermediate Technology Publications]] |isbn=185339386X |oclc=36589868 |page=106}}</ref>

By the early 1980s, there was growing dissatisfaction among development experts with both the reductionism of formal surveys, and the biases of typical field visits. In 1983, Robert Chambers, a Fellow at the [[Institute of Development Studies]] (UK), used the term ''rapid rural appraisal'' (RRA) to describe techniques that could bring about a "reversal of learning", to learn from rural people directly.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Chambers |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Chambers (development scholar) |date=April 1981 |title=Rapid rural appraisal: rationale and repertoire |journal=Public Administration and Development |volume=1 |issue=2 |pages=95–106 |doi=10.1002/pad.4230010202 |url=http://www.parkdatabase.org/documents/download/1981_chambers_rapid_rural_appraisal_rationale_and_repertoire_3.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Chambers |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Chambers (development scholar) |date=1984 |origyear=1983 |title=Rural development: putting the last first |location=London; New York |publisher=[[Longman]] |isbn=0582644437 |oclc=9196254 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zLeOAwAAQBAJ}}</ref> Two years later, the first international conference to share experiences relating to RRA was held in Thailand.<ref>{{cite book |title=Proceedings of the 1985 International Conference on Rapid Rural Appraisal: Khon Kaen University |date=1987 |location=Khon Kaen, Thailand |publisher=Published by Rural Systems Research Project and Farming Systems Research Project for [[Khon Kaen University]] |isbn=9789745552517 |oclc=19025969}}</ref> This was followed by a rapid acceptance of usage of methods that involved rural people in examining their own problems, setting their own goals, and monitoring their own achievements. By the mid 1990s, the term RRA had been replaced by a number of other terms including ''participatory rural appraisal'' (PRA) and ''participatory learning and action'' (PLA).<ref>[https://books.google.com/ngrams/graph?content=participatory+rural+appraisal%2Cparticipatory+learning+and+action&case_insensitive=on&year_start=1980&year_end=2008&corpus=15&smoothing=3 Search results for 'participatory rural appraisal' and 'participatory learning and action'] on [[Google Ngram Viewer]]</ref>

Robert Chambers acknowledged that the significant breakthroughs and innovations that informed the methodology came from community development practitioners in Africa, India and elsewhere. Chambers helped PRA gain acceptance among practitioners.<ref>{{cite book |last=Singh |first=Kamal |date=2001 |chapter=Handing over the stick: the global spread of participatory approaches to development |editor1-last=Edwards |editor1-first=Michael |editor2-last=Gaventa |editor2-first=John |title=Global citizen action |location=Boulder, Colorado |publisher=[[Lynne Rienner Publishers]] |pages=175–187 |isbn=1555879683 |oclc=45879585 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=bshQAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA175}}</ref> Chambers explained the function of participatory research in PRA as follows:

{{quote |text=The central thrusts of the [new] paradigm … are decentralization and empowerment. Decentralization means that resources and discretion are devolved, turning back the inward and upward flows of resources and people. Empowerment means that people, especially poorer people, are enabled to take more control over their lives, and secure a better livelihood with ownership and control of productive assets as one key element. Decentralization and empowerment enable local people to exploit the diverse complexities of their own conditions, and to adapt to rapid change.<ref>{{cite book |last=Chambers |first=Robert |authorlink=Robert Chambers (development scholar) |date=1993 |title=Challenging the professions: frontiers for rural development |location=London |publisher=[[Intermediate Technology Development Group|Intermediate Technology Publications]] |isbn=1853391948 |oclc=28470414}}</ref>}}

== Overview of techniques ==
Over the years techniques and tools have been described in a variety of books and newsletters, or taught at training courses.<ref name="Chambers origins"/><ref name="Pretty Vodouhe">{{cite book |last1=Pretty |first1=Jules N. |last2=Vodouhê |first2=Simplice D. |date=1997 |origyear=1984 |chapter=Using rapid or participatory rural appraisal |editor1-last=Swanson |editor1-first=Burton E. |editor2-last=Bentz |editor2-first=Robert P. |editor3-last=Sofranko |editor3-first=Andrew J. |title=Improving agricultural extension: a reference manual |edition=2nd |location=Rome |publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization]] of the [[United Nations]] |isbn=9251040079 |oclc=456586976 |chapterurl=http://www.fao.org/docrep/W5830E/w5830e08.htm}}</ref><ref name="Sontheimer et al">{{cite book |last1=Sontheimer |first1=Sally |last2=Callens |first2=Karel |last3=Seiffert |first3=Bernd |date=1999 |chapter=PRA tool box |title=Conducting a PRA training and modifying PRA tools to your needs: an example from a participatory household food security and nutrition project in Ethiopia |location=Rome |publisher=[[Food and Agriculture Organization]] of the [[United Nations]] |chapterurl=http://www.fao.org/docrep/003/X5996E/x5996e06.htm}}</ref> However, the field has been criticized for lacking a systematic evidence-based methodology.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Leurs |first=Robert |date=August 1997 |title=Critical reflections on rapid and participatory rural appraisal |journal=Development in Practice |volume=7 |issue=3 |pages=290–293 |jstor=4029070 |url=http://www.developmentinpractice.org/journals/critical-reflections-rapid-and-participatory-rural-appraisal}}</ref>

The basic techniques used include:<ref name="Chambers origins"/><ref name="Castelloe Gamble"/><ref name="Narayanasamy"/><ref name="Pretty Vodouhe"/><ref name="Sontheimer et al"/>
* Understanding [[group dynamics]], e.g. through learning contracts, [[role reversal]]s, feedback sessions
* Surveying and [[Sampling (statistics)|sampling]], e.g. transect walks, wealth ranking, social mapping
* [[Interview (research)|Interviewing]], e.g. [[focus group]] discussions, [[semi-structured interview]]s, [[Triangulation (social science)|triangulation]]
* [[Information visualization|Community mapping]], e.g. [[Venn diagram]]s, [[Matrix (mathematics)|matrix]] scoring, [[Eco-map|ecogram]]s, [[timeline]]s

To ensure that people are not excluded from participation, these techniques avoid [[writing]] wherever possible, relying instead on the tools of [[orality|oral communication]] and [[visual communication]] such as pictures, symbols, physical objects and group memory.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Robinson-Pant |first=Anna |date=1995 |title=PRA: a new literacy? |journal=PLA Notes |volume=24 |pages=78–82 |url=http://pubs.iied.org/G01605/}}</ref> Efforts are made in many projects, however, to build a bridge to formal [[literacy]]; for example by teaching people how to sign their names or recognize their signatures. Often developing communities are reluctant to permit invasive audio-visual recording.{{Citation needed|date=February 2017}}

== Developmental changes in PRA ==
Since the early 21st century, some practitioners have replaced PRA with the standardized model of [[community-based participatory research]] (CBPR) or with [[participatory action research]] (PAR).{{Citation needed|date=February 2017}} Social survey techniques have also changed during this period, including greater use of [[information technology]] such as [[fuzzy cognitive map]]s, [[e-participation]], [[telepresence]], [[social network analysis]], [[topic model]]s, [[geographic information system]]s (GIS), and [[interactive multimedia]].{{Citation needed|date=February 2017}}

