The '''Rostock Peace Treaty''' ({{lang-de|Rostocker Landfrieden}}) was a treaty, or ''[[Landfriede]]'', agreed on 13 June 1283 in [[Rostock]] to secure the peace on land and at sea, as well as the protection of taxes and other freedoms. The parties to the treaty agreed that, for ten years, they would avoid the use of force in exercising their rights. This treaty was the foundation for the economic growth of [[Wismar]] and other medieval seaports on the [[Baltic Sea]].
The signatories to the treaty were the [[Hanseatic town]]s of [[Lübeck]], [[Rostock]], [[Wismar]], [[Stralsund]], [[Greifswald]], [[Stettin]], [[Demmin]] and [[Anklam]] as well as the dukes of [[Duchy of Saxony|Saxony]] and [[Duchy of Pomerania|Pomerania]], the Prince of [[Principality of Rügen|Rügen]], the lords of [[County of Schwerin|Schwerin]] and [[County of Dannenberg|Dannenberg]] as well as the lesser nobility of Rostock.
== Literature == * Wolf-Dieter Mohrmann: ''Der Landfriede im Ostseeraum während des späten Mittelalters'', 1972, {{ISBN|3784740022}}
